SIMPLE: herald
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Herald
<hw>Her"ald</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>herald</ets>, <ets>heraud</ets>, OF. <ets>heralt</ets>,
<ets>heraut</ets>, <ets>herault</ets>, F. <ets>h⟦eacute⟧raut</ets>, LL.
<ets>heraldus</ets>, <ets>haraldus</ets>, fr. (assumed) OHG.
<ets>heriwalto</ets>, <ets>hariwaldo</ets>, a (civil) officer who serves
the army; <ets>hari</ets>, <ets>heri</ets>, army + <ets>waltan</ets> to
manage, govern, G. <ets>walten</ets>; akin to E. <ets>wield</ets>. See
<er>Harry</er>, <er>Wield</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Antiq.)</fld>
<def>An officer whose business was to denounce or proclaim war, to
challenge to battle, to proclaim peace, and to bear messages from the
commander of an army. He was invested with a sacred and inviolable
character.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 687 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In the Middle Ages, the officer charged with the
above duties, and also with the care of genealogies, of the rights and
privileges of noble families, and especially of armorial bearings. In
modern times, some vestiges of this office remain, especially in
England. See <cref>Heralds' College</cref> (below), and
<er>King-at-Arms</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A proclaimer; one who, or that which, publishes or
announces; <as>as, the <ex>herald</ex> of another's fame</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A forerunner; a a precursor; a harbinger.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was the lark, the <qex>herald</qex> of the morn.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Any messenger.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧My <xex>herald</xex> is
returned.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Heralds' College</b></col>, <cd>in England, an ancient
corporation, dependent upon the crown, instituted or perhaps recognized
by Richard III. in 1483, consisting of the three Kings-at-Arms and the
Chester, Lancaster, Richmond, Somerset, Windsor, and York Heralds,
together with the Earl Marshal. This retains from the Middle Ages the
charge of the armorial bearings of persons privileged to bear them, as
well as of genealogies and kindred subjects; -- called also
<altname>College of Arms</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Herald</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Herald
<hw>Her"ald</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Heralded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Heralding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>herauder</ets>,
<ets>heraulder</ets>.]</ety> <def>To introduce, or give tidings of, as
by a herald; to proclaim; to announce; to foretell; to usher in.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>heralded</ent>⟦br⟧
